WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

1
00:00:35.070 --> 00:00:42.050
Horror has always been an inherently traditionalistic
genre, since fear is an inherently traditional,

2
00:00:42.050 --> 00:00:47.650
conservative emotion, and horror is often
used for preserving traditional values: the

3
00:00:47.650 --> 00:00:54.080
victory of those who are virtuous, the punishment
of those who are wicked, and rejection of

4
00:00:54.080 --> 00:00:55.080
the “other”.

5
00:00:55.080 --> 00:00:59.600
Nevertheless, for centuries, queerness and
horror have been inextricably linked.

6
00:00:59.600 --> 00:01:03.930
With horror relying on queerness for shock
value, and queerness relying on horror for

7
00:01:03.930 --> 00:01:06.440
visibility and validation.

8
00:01:06.440 --> 00:01:10.760
The horror genre we know today has its roots
in the eighteenth-century romance and Gothic

9
00:01:10.760 --> 00:01:15.850
genres, the more gruesome works of Shakespeare,
as well as the works of Dante, which described

10
00:01:15.850 --> 00:01:20.890
in graphic detail the torments of Hell that
await those who sin.

11
00:01:20.890 --> 00:01:26.130
But the arrival of the printing press spurred
a demand for long-format literature.

12
00:01:26.130 --> 00:01:30.620
Enter the Gothic genre, and the growing dominance
of the novel as the go-to English language

13
00:01:30.620 --> 00:01:33.060
prose-fiction format.

14
00:01:33.060 --> 00:01:34.640
More demand meant more authors.

15
00:01:34.640 --> 00:01:36.430
More authors meant more voices.

16
00:01:36.430 --> 00:01:38.130
Namely, queer voices.

17
00:01:38.130 --> 00:01:43.110
However, we would only step into the spotlight
as one of the few great leading roles we were

18
00:01:43.110 --> 00:01:47.250
allowed to fully inhabit: The Villain.

19
00:01:47.250 --> 00:01:51.640
Queer attraction and subtext could suddenly
be explored in works like Sheridan Le Fanu's

20
00:01:51.640 --> 00:01:57.450
Carmilla, Oscar Wilde's The Picture of Dorian
Gray, and Bram Stoker's Dracula, and queer

21
00:01:57.450 --> 00:02:02.530
characters could take a role at the heart
of the story, albeit as predatory monsters

22
00:02:02.530 --> 00:02:04.630
with perverse desires.

23
00:02:04.630 --> 00:02:10.190
LGBT authors discovered that we could operate
within the constraints of this most conservative

24
00:02:10.190 --> 00:02:15.070
genres, utilizing metaphor and coding to depict
our queer culture…

25
00:02:15.070 --> 00:02:21.780
For a while, it was preferable to be seen
as a monster rather than to go unnoticed.

26
00:02:21.780 --> 00:02:26.620
However, in our eagerness to use the genre
to depict some element of ourselves, we most

27
00:02:26.620 --> 00:02:33.310
frequently revealed our self-hatred, the stinging
toxin gay readers were obliged to ingest in

28
00:02:33.310 --> 00:02:37.020
order to fulfill our desire to see ourselves.

29
00:02:37.020 --> 00:02:42.660
Into the early 1900s, through two world wars
and the extremely conformist 1950s and early

30
00:02:42.660 --> 00:02:48.579
1960s, so-called sexual deviation and perversity
continued to play a prominent part in the

31
00:02:48.579 --> 00:02:49.970
horror genre.

32
00:02:49.970 --> 00:02:55.169
As novels, movies, and television became increasingly
permissive, graphic depictions of passionate

33
00:02:55.169 --> 00:03:01.730
lesbian vampires, pansexual covens, mother-obsessed
maniacs, and cross-dressing cannibals startled

34
00:03:01.730 --> 00:03:07.470
and titilated mainstream audiences... while
infuriating censors, and many in the queer

35
00:03:07.470 --> 00:03:08.770
community alike.

36
00:03:08.770 --> 00:03:14.669
But the anti-hero was becoming a prominent
protagonist now, and the prim, prudish, heterosexual

37
00:03:14.669 --> 00:03:20.540
heroes of the past were ridiculed for being
painfully boring, while the bizarre monsters

38
00:03:20.540 --> 00:03:24.490
and murderers were applauded for their defiance
of societal conventions.

39
00:03:24.490 --> 00:03:29.670
Up until then, families were considered a
perfect microcosm of society.

40
00:03:29.670 --> 00:03:30.670
Sacred.

41
00:03:30.670 --> 00:03:32.410
A source of power and security.

42
00:03:32.410 --> 00:03:36.910
The heroes would do whatever was required
to defeat the monster and restore order, including

43
00:03:36.910 --> 00:03:38.440
sacrificing themselves.

44
00:03:38.440 --> 00:03:41.660
But then a transition took place.

45
00:03:41.660 --> 00:03:46.560
We went from 'killing the deviant to save
the family and society' to the insinuation

46
00:03:46.560 --> 00:03:52.010
that family and society was where the deviance
lay, and that they may destroy you.

47
00:03:52.010 --> 00:03:56.840
Rosemary’s Baby, Carrie, The Exorcist, The
Shining, and The Omen.

48
00:03:56.840 --> 00:04:03.730
In these stories, family and society were
where the monsters were made… through divorce,

49
00:04:03.730 --> 00:04:10.479
abuse, or neglect… through isolation and
exclusion, and especially through a disregard

50
00:04:10.479 --> 00:04:16.549
for and degradation of the rules of gender
and sexual identity that “good families”

51
00:04:16.549 --> 00:04:17.549
obeyed.

52
00:04:17.549 --> 00:04:20.220
This was the new order of things in horror.

53
00:04:20.220 --> 00:04:24.660
These stories were in high contrast with those
of decades prior, where the monster was still

54
00:04:24.660 --> 00:04:28.220
an external force we could fight and destroy.

55
00:04:28.220 --> 00:04:33.090
In recent years, the queer villain/anti-hero
has made an interesting and largely welcome

56
00:04:33.090 --> 00:04:38.210
return within horror, as we have seen an increase
in the psychological complexity of its monsters

57
00:04:38.210 --> 00:04:42.540
and the conflicted nature of its heroes and
victims.

58
00:04:42.540 --> 00:04:47.470
Anne Rice’s vampires come to mind as an
example, as well as Bryan Fuller’s TV series,

59
00:04:47.470 --> 00:04:48.620
Hannibal.

60
00:04:48.620 --> 00:04:55.210
In pervious horror-themed videos I’ve discussed
the drawn empathy between queer peoples and

61
00:04:55.210 --> 00:04:56.210
monsters.

62
00:04:56.210 --> 00:05:00.500
We see ourselves in monsters because we have
also been cast out of society.

63
00:05:00.500 --> 00:05:05.900
We’ve been decreed unfit for all audiences,
something we must protect women and children

64
00:05:05.900 --> 00:05:06.900
from.

65
00:05:06.900 --> 00:05:13.040
We must be regulated, and if necessary, slain
— for no other reason than how we are different

66
00:05:13.040 --> 00:05:14.650
from society’s expectations.

67
00:05:14.650 --> 00:05:19.750
So we look at Frankenstein’s creation and
think, well, I’m also a social outcast,

68
00:05:19.750 --> 00:05:20.750
and I have feelings.

69
00:05:20.750 --> 00:05:25.320
I have a heart, and aspirations, social needs,
and dreams of living a good life.

70
00:05:25.320 --> 00:05:27.540
Shouldn’t that mean that he does also?

71
00:05:27.540 --> 00:05:28.540
But there’s something that’s overlooked.

72
00:05:28.540 --> 00:05:33.760
That queer people are fundamentally the same
as straight people.

73
00:05:33.760 --> 00:05:39.900
And just as there is narcissism, ego, exploitation,
and abuse among straight people — When it

74
00:05:39.900 --> 00:05:43.920
comes to queer people… sometimes a monster…
is just a monster.

75
00:05:43.920 --> 00:05:50.300
It’s like we — queer people in our relationships
— are so conditioned to seeing the person

76
00:05:50.300 --> 00:05:55.900
behind the monster that we overlook the elements
that are genuinely monstrous because to us,

77
00:05:55.900 --> 00:06:01.710
as historical societal outcasts who lacked
connection to human society at large, we value

78
00:06:01.710 --> 00:06:07.090
the human connection enough to tolerate or
even condone monstrous behaviour.

79
00:06:07.090 --> 00:06:12.740
And yes, we’re always on the lookout for
monsters who want to eat your heart.

80
00:06:12.740 --> 00:06:17.730
But far more insidious is the monster that
wants to eat your mind.

81
00:06:17.730 --> 00:06:19.580
Your self worth.

82
00:06:19.580 --> 00:06:28.900
And we seem to be very comfortable with those
monsters.

83
00:06:28.900 --> 00:06:38.840
Over the course of its three seasons, Hannibal,
lead by out gay show-runner Bryan Fuller,

84
00:06:38.840 --> 00:06:43.090
made a significant impact on both the horror
and crime drama fandoms.

85
00:06:43.090 --> 00:06:49.630
With a focus on comprehending the psychology
of serial killers — the driving line of

86
00:06:49.630 --> 00:06:56.030
the show was built around learning how to
develop human connections with people who

87
00:06:56.030 --> 00:06:57.800
lack humanity.

88
00:06:57.800 --> 00:07:01.080
Empathy for those who cannot empathize.

89
00:07:01.080 --> 00:07:05.389
The emotional through-line of the show, however,
is built around the relationship between the

90
00:07:05.389 --> 00:07:10.830
titular antagonist Hannibal Lecter, and the
Psychological Profiler Will Graham.

91
00:07:10.830 --> 00:07:15.690
In the book Red Dragon the story begins, and
the infamous Dr. Lecter — Hannibal the Cannibal

92
00:07:15.690 --> 00:07:18.190
— is incarcerated.

93
00:07:18.190 --> 00:07:23.010
Will Graham is recruited by the FBI to track
down a serial killer, and it’s referenced

94
00:07:23.010 --> 00:07:27.810
that this is not the first time the FBI has
approached Will for consultation.

95
00:07:27.810 --> 00:07:34.650
Apparently, Will and the FBI had worked with
Hannibal Lecter, who was a practicing psychiatrist,

96
00:07:34.650 --> 00:07:37.650
to profile one of a number of serial killers.

97
00:07:37.650 --> 00:07:42.940
Eventually, Will realized it was Hannibal
who was the killer that they were tracking,

98
00:07:42.940 --> 00:07:46.250
and Hannibal nearly killed him before he was
arrested.

99
00:07:46.250 --> 00:07:50.940
The result was a complete fallout with the
FBI, and Will himself coping with the trauma

100
00:07:50.940 --> 00:07:57.040
for years before Agent Jack Crawford tracked
him down again to help with a case.

101
00:07:57.040 --> 00:08:00.680
But through the mystery of the Red Dragon,
there are constant call backs to Will’s

102
00:08:00.680 --> 00:08:06.260
work with the FBI and his twisted relationship
with Hannibal, which… it’s hinted... that

103
00:08:06.260 --> 00:08:09.389
they were much closer than we’re being led
to believe.

104
00:08:09.389 --> 00:08:14.280
The Hannibal TV series for NBC focused around
filling in these plot details.

105
00:08:14.280 --> 00:08:16.560
What would a relationship between Hannibal
and Will be like?

106
00:08:16.560 --> 00:08:19.020
How did they get to that point in Red Dragon?

107
00:08:19.020 --> 00:08:21.160
What did it take to bring Hannibal down?

108
00:08:21.160 --> 00:08:26.639
And most importantly, appropriately presenting
Will Graham in a way that honours his collection

109
00:08:26.639 --> 00:08:29.760
of neurotic behaviours that were outlined
in the book.

110
00:08:29.760 --> 00:08:35.610
In the series, Will Graham is a cocktail of
personality disorders, as he describes, closer

111
00:08:35.610 --> 00:08:40.449
to autism and aspergers than an antisocial
personality disorder.

112
00:08:40.449 --> 00:08:45.620
Will is able to look at a setting, and accurately
describe an individual based on cues within

113
00:08:45.620 --> 00:08:46.620
the scene.

114
00:08:46.620 --> 00:08:51.230
Now while this could do wonders on Drag Race
for reading the other queens—

115
00:08:51.230 --> 00:08:58.000
—this has a very practical application for
crime scene investigation.

116
00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:02.720
By looking at the scene of a murder, Will
can slip into the mind of the killer.

117
00:09:02.720 --> 00:09:07.730
He can observe clues, see the sequence of
the events, and then construct the psychological

118
00:09:07.730 --> 00:09:13.930
profile of the person who did the murder based
on who he becomes while he re-expiriences

119
00:09:13.930 --> 00:09:14.930
it.

120
00:09:14.930 --> 00:09:18.650
Developing a profile of a serial killer is
useful in determining how they select their

121
00:09:18.650 --> 00:09:19.650
targets.

122
00:09:19.650 --> 00:09:24.430
Given how most serial killers operate, figuring
out how they select their victims could lead

123
00:09:24.430 --> 00:09:29.370
investigators to where the serial killers
live, or intercept them before they kill again.

124
00:09:29.370 --> 00:09:34.590
From observing these crime scenes, Will can
figure out how they think and what they think

125
00:09:34.590 --> 00:09:36.700
about their victims.

126
00:09:36.700 --> 00:09:42.490
Will, from a perspective of self-analysis,
reports to the FBI what he feels and thinks

127
00:09:42.490 --> 00:09:44.550
when he re-lives the murder.

128
00:09:44.550 --> 00:09:48.391
A psychological profile is constructed based
on who Will says he becomes.

129
00:09:48.391 --> 00:09:53.400
In the mythology of the show, Will’s perspective
is second-to-none.

130
00:09:53.400 --> 00:09:59.230
Now, for Will, that does mean that he has
to distance himself from his own mind and

131
00:09:59.230 --> 00:10:05.360
take on the world view of people who conduct
very… elaborate crimes.

132
00:10:05.360 --> 00:10:10.191
Naturally this kind of identity flux is of
immense interest to Dr. Hannibal Lecter, who

133
00:10:10.191 --> 00:10:14.680
first wants to study Will, but then as he
learns the extent of Will’s ability, begins

134
00:10:14.680 --> 00:10:17.380
to feel the need to transform Will.

135
00:10:17.380 --> 00:10:21.930
Hannibal has an unparalleled capacity to read
and interpret body language.

136
00:10:21.930 --> 00:10:26.550
Contrast to Will’s ability to construct
human models based on reading environment.

137
00:10:26.550 --> 00:10:31.950
He sees Will’s neurotic behaviour as the
result of Will rejecting elements of his own

138
00:10:31.950 --> 00:10:32.950
identity.

139
00:10:32.950 --> 00:10:37.050
Hannibal feels that Will's ability to see
into the heads of serial killers is an indication

140
00:10:37.050 --> 00:10:42.610
that Will is drawn to these people — and
that Will can only be his true self while

141
00:10:42.610 --> 00:10:57.050
he is re-experiencing these murders.

142
00:10:57.050 --> 00:11:02.760
The show is ambiguous about whether this is
or is not, in fact, the case.

143
00:11:02.760 --> 00:11:07.690
Will seems to adapt his personality to whoever
he is with — so what Hannibal sees may be

144
00:11:07.690 --> 00:11:10.980
a reflection of himself, instead of the real
Will.

145
00:11:10.980 --> 00:11:16.500
His interactions with Will are most likely
to be a matter of Hannibal interacting with

146
00:11:16.500 --> 00:11:22.330
Will’s interpretation of Hannibal.

147
00:11:22.330 --> 00:11:26.600
But this is the psychology of fictional characters
so take it with a grain of salt.

148
00:11:26.600 --> 00:11:31.420
While the show begins as a kind of... best
possible version of a procedural cop drama,

149
00:11:31.420 --> 00:11:35.550
the serial killing becomes a vessel for Hannibal
and Will to connect.

150
00:11:35.550 --> 00:11:40.300
Two men who keep people at arms length because
they fear human contact for one reason or

151
00:11:40.300 --> 00:11:41.300
another.

152
00:11:41.300 --> 00:11:46.100
Through a discourse on why Will feels the
way he does, he is drawn to someone who offers

153
00:11:46.100 --> 00:11:52.880
him clarity of identity.

154
00:11:52.880 --> 00:12:03.610
And through the process of Will empathising
with monsters, Hannibal is comforted in knowing

155
00:12:03.610 --> 00:12:07.680
that there is someone who could and would
understand him.

156
00:12:07.680 --> 00:12:14.360
And while Hannibal takes peevish delight in
being beyond comprehension…

157
00:12:14.360 --> 00:12:22.540
…Mads Michelson delivers a Hannibal that
is yearning for contact with a human from

158
00:12:22.540 --> 00:12:26.830
whom he does not have to leverage emotional
intimacy with.

159
00:12:26.830 --> 00:12:27.830
Now.

160
00:12:27.830 --> 00:12:31.740
There’s hardly a discourse to be had here
that actively verifies the textual evidence

161
00:12:31.740 --> 00:12:40.680
to confirm that Will and Hannibal are more
or less romantically engaged.

162
00:12:40.680 --> 00:12:49.720
It really doubles down on the gay stuff as
the show goes on, but it was still there in

163
00:12:49.720 --> 00:12:51.330
season 1.

164
00:12:51.330 --> 00:12:58.400
But I’m not sure you can qualify it as GAY
representation in its purist sense.

165
00:12:58.400 --> 00:13:03.310
Both because the show’s driving relationship
existed in subtext, but also because the development

166
00:13:03.310 --> 00:13:09.450
of Will and Hannibal was focused around empathizing
with people who we maybe should not empathize

167
00:13:09.450 --> 00:13:10.450
with.

168
00:13:10.450 --> 00:13:15.350
But it’s some of the best and most insightful
queer coding that’s ever made it into a

169
00:13:15.350 --> 00:13:16.430
visual medium.

170
00:13:16.430 --> 00:13:21.070
These are two men, coping with different kinds
of deep-seeded trauma from their youth.

171
00:13:21.070 --> 00:13:26.880
They keep themselves isolated and distant
because they are familiar with society’s

172
00:13:26.880 --> 00:13:30.020
fear or disgust with what they are.

173
00:13:30.020 --> 00:13:34.870
One hides in plain sight, holding a shield
of lavish opulence that enchants those around

174
00:13:34.870 --> 00:13:40.160
him into believing that nobody this gentlemanly
and eccentric could be anything else.

175
00:13:40.160 --> 00:13:44.670
The other, keeps himself physically distant,
preferring the unconditional friendship of

176
00:13:44.670 --> 00:13:45.670
animals.

177
00:13:45.670 --> 00:13:48.529
Brilliant, solitary, engrossed in their hobbies.

178
00:13:48.529 --> 00:13:51.660
They dream of normality, paternity — being
in a family.

179
00:13:51.660 --> 00:13:57.140
Though they have both reserved themselves
to their lives, and their fantasies.

180
00:13:57.140 --> 00:14:01.630
And when they meet, by complete accident,
they recognize that they see their own fantasies

181
00:14:01.630 --> 00:14:06.050
in the other, making steps to develop their
own kind of family — from the people who

182
00:14:06.050 --> 00:14:07.380
need them most.

183
00:14:07.380 --> 00:14:14.830
The main difference is that… one of them
knowingly eats people.

184
00:14:14.830 --> 00:14:16.840
And this is just the thing, right?

185
00:14:16.840 --> 00:14:19.650
It’s very clearly gay without saying it
is.

186
00:14:19.650 --> 00:14:24.090
In fact, by all accounts, Bryan Fuller fully
intended to give Will and Hannibal an explicit

187
00:14:24.090 --> 00:14:25.380
romantic arc.

188
00:14:25.380 --> 00:14:31.170
Mads Michelson said that during the filming
of the last scene of Season 3, he was trying

189
00:14:31.170 --> 00:14:33.930
very hard not to kiss Hugh Dancy.

190
00:14:33.930 --> 00:14:35.650
That’s… not acting, apparently.

191
00:14:35.650 --> 00:14:39.510
The intention to canonize the Hannibal and
Will relationship may also be one of the reasons

192
00:14:39.510 --> 00:14:43.550
why NBC didn’t move ahead with a 4th season.

193
00:14:43.550 --> 00:14:47.220
Because although there were lesbian characters
on the show, lesbians are famously more easy

194
00:14:47.220 --> 00:14:48.730
to sell to advertisers.

195
00:14:48.730 --> 00:14:51.800
Which is why you see a lot more lesbian rep
in kids cartoons these days.

196
00:14:51.800 --> 00:14:56.240
But gay characters, at least gay lead characters,
are still something that network TV shies

197
00:14:56.240 --> 00:14:57.240
away from.

198
00:14:57.240 --> 00:15:01.700
It’s that threat of penetration that creeps
under the skin of a lot of executives and

199
00:15:01.700 --> 00:15:03.200
viewers.

200
00:15:03.200 --> 00:15:07.080
Subconsciously creating an unease around gay
men that isn’t there for gay women.

201
00:15:07.080 --> 00:15:09.560
At least as long as the gay women look like
this.

202
00:15:09.560 --> 00:15:14.060
But in spite of the avid, and continuing flow
of fan art depicting Mickelson and Dancy in

203
00:15:14.060 --> 00:15:20.320
compromising postions donning varying degrees
of undress, I’m not only hesitant to label

204
00:15:20.320 --> 00:15:25.040
this as good gay representation, I’m slightly
resistant to it.

205
00:15:25.040 --> 00:15:29.510
God forbid we have a generation of gays who
describe themselves as a Hannigram power couple.

206
00:15:29.510 --> 00:15:34.960
What they have, while intense and fun to watch,
is still… very toxic.

207
00:15:34.960 --> 00:15:41.970
You’ve got a know-it-all, gaslighting, mansplainer
on one hand.

208
00:15:41.970 --> 00:15:45.019
And on the other, you have a passive-aggressive,
self-victimizing martyr.

209
00:15:45.019 --> 00:15:47.690
That should not be relationship goals.

210
00:15:47.690 --> 00:15:51.160
And while there are fans who realize that
no, the point of the show is that you should

211
00:15:51.160 --> 00:15:55.880
probably get some help if you see yourself
as Will and/or Hannibal, there’s quite a

212
00:15:55.880 --> 00:16:02.450
romantic drive in the show’s fanbase.

213
00:16:02.450 --> 00:16:14.990
I’ve even seen the show be compared abundantly
to the online comics Killing Stalking and

214
00:16:14.990 --> 00:16:19.540
Warehouse, and I see where the take is coming
from, but I’m not entirely sure that I agree

215
00:16:19.540 --> 00:16:20.570
with it.

216
00:16:20.570 --> 00:16:24.550
Killing Stalking is a story about a serial
killer who has complete dominant control over

217
00:16:24.550 --> 00:16:25.660
another man.

218
