within our marginalized community.

654
00:45:14.170 --> 00:45:17.840
Queers who live with disabilities, or who
are mentally ill.

655
00:45:17.840 --> 00:45:22.500
When being queer isn’t the only reason someone
might not love you, we’ll hold on to whatever

656
00:45:22.500 --> 00:45:24.230
and whoever we can get.

657
00:45:24.230 --> 00:45:26.700
No matter what they do to us.

658
00:45:26.700 --> 00:45:31.100
No matter how little we mean to them.

659
00:45:31.100 --> 00:45:46.260
Because at least we mean something to them.

660
00:45:46.260 --> 00:45:51.970
As we engage with our media, the relationship
between queer people and monsters becomes

661
00:45:51.970 --> 00:45:52.970
stronger.

662
00:45:52.970 --> 00:45:59.700
There’s always been a component of monstrousness
in the inner circles of queer spaces — specifically

663
00:45:59.700 --> 00:46:03.460
in the areas of kink, drag, and performance.

664
00:46:03.460 --> 00:46:09.620
It should come as a surprise to no one that
the booming popularity of adults going into

665
00:46:09.620 --> 00:46:17.250
mouth-foaming frenzies for halloween arose
as queer people began receiving social and

666
00:46:17.250 --> 00:46:18.560
political recognition

667
00:46:18.560 --> 00:46:24.630
Queer people have a fascination with costumes
— and this is something documented for most

668
00:46:24.630 --> 00:46:27.740
of our time in recorded history.

669
00:46:27.740 --> 00:46:33.550
As social outsiders, there’s nothing more
appealing than becoming someone who is publicly

670
00:46:33.550 --> 00:46:35.750
accepted.

671
00:46:35.750 --> 00:46:42.420
Even if that costume was just a plain old
normal person.

672
00:46:42.420 --> 00:46:48.870
When what’s under your skin is decried as
being freakish, you begin to see everything

673
00:46:48.870 --> 00:46:54.980
as a costume — especially the conventions
of society that are taken for granted.

674
00:46:54.980 --> 00:46:56.440
The business suit.

675
00:46:56.440 --> 00:46:57.790
The Sunday dress.

676
00:46:57.790 --> 00:46:59.580
The fake smile.

677
00:46:59.580 --> 00:47:03.130
The things you wear to fit in with the straights.

678
00:47:03.130 --> 00:47:09.730
Alternately, where once we were artists, creators,
rule breakers in our day to day lives, now

679
00:47:09.730 --> 00:47:15.110
our creativity and rule-breaking may be tolerated
for certain events.

680
00:47:15.110 --> 00:47:16.790
Halloween.

681
00:47:16.790 --> 00:47:18.560
Pride parades.

682
00:47:18.560 --> 00:47:22.150
Certain fairs where we can be ourselves.

683
00:47:22.150 --> 00:47:27.340
And then there are the… twinks and gym bunnies
who put on a jock strap and harness and dance

684
00:47:27.340 --> 00:47:28.630
on some tables.

685
00:47:28.630 --> 00:47:30.350
A costume all its own.

686
00:47:30.350 --> 00:47:36.610
A problem with focusing so clearly on Halloween
and pride week as spaces where ‘true selves’

687
00:47:36.610 --> 00:47:41.890
are acceptable is that we are being harassed
out of being our ‘true selves’ for the

688
00:47:41.890 --> 00:47:43.020
rest of the year.

689
00:47:43.020 --> 00:47:49.740
If you’re so excited for pride week so that
you can be a seven-day slut, why are you so

690
00:47:49.740 --> 00:47:54.180
ashamed of sexual promiscuity for the other
fifty-one weeks?

691
00:47:54.180 --> 00:48:01.520
Obviously, this is how you want to live your
life — why are you tolerating only ONE week

692
00:48:01.520 --> 00:48:11.570
where this behaviour is ‘permissible’
or even only tolerable by straight social-gatekeepers?

693
00:48:11.570 --> 00:48:17.450
Modern manifestations of queer circles are
facing these struggles, as the cisgender-heterosexual

694
00:48:17.450 --> 00:48:23.170
hegimony imparts more and more statutes for
conditional tolerance.

695
00:48:23.170 --> 00:48:30.330
You can be accepted, but only if you can check
off A, B, and C on the application for public

696
00:48:30.330 --> 00:48:32.620
recognition.

697
00:48:32.620 --> 00:48:37.930
This is just a more nuanced version of outrightly
shutting out these identities and lifestyles

698
00:48:37.930 --> 00:48:39.740
as a whole.

699
00:48:39.740 --> 00:48:45.270
Instead, SOME queer people can naturally fit
into these parameters.

700
00:48:45.270 --> 00:48:50.400
Others will force themselves to conform for
the sake of social comforts and conveniences.

701
00:48:50.400 --> 00:48:53.010
Others are either unable to conform, or refuse
to.

702
00:48:53.010 --> 00:48:56.610
And why should they have to?

703
00:48:56.610 --> 00:49:02.930
Forcing hegemonistic spaces to remove restrictions
on a social definition of personhood — rather

704
00:49:02.930 --> 00:49:09.480
than broadening an increasingly-complex cataloge
of valid identities — should be the main

705
00:49:09.480 --> 00:49:13.900
objective of queer rights, I think.

706
00:49:13.900 --> 00:49:21.420
Instead, we record and document every sub-genre
of sexuality and gender — deciding who can

707
00:49:21.420 --> 00:49:23.490
be valid and when.

708
00:49:23.490 --> 00:49:30.800
Instead of just realizing it’s nobody’s
business and letting people live their lives…

709
00:49:30.800 --> 00:49:38.079
we are relegating queer noncomformists to
exist in the shadows.

710
00:49:38.079 --> 00:49:43.330
And in the shadows, there are always monsters.

711
00:49:43.330 --> 00:49:47.520
Given that queer circles at large were once
forced to live in the shadows, maybe this

712
00:49:47.520 --> 00:49:50.610
is why we’ve always been drawn to the monsters
within them.

713
00:49:50.610 --> 00:49:56.300
There’s also a theatrical element to the
beast, isn’t there?

714
00:49:56.300 --> 00:50:02.910
An ethereal fantasy constructed around the
Alfar of northern europe.

715
00:50:02.910 --> 00:50:06.860
The strength and poise of the faefolk of the
Celts.

716
00:50:06.860 --> 00:50:12.230
Oberon, The Earlking, and their court of nature
spirits of southern France and Germany that

717
00:50:12.230 --> 00:50:16.720
survived the collapse of the Roman Empire.

718
00:50:16.720 --> 00:50:20.200
All stories banned by the authority of the
Catholic Church.

719
00:50:20.200 --> 00:50:26.750
And each figure recategorized as a servant
of Satan.

720
00:50:26.750 --> 00:50:32.310
But the nature of our secret, solicit meetings
facilitated an exchange of ideas between the

721
00:50:32.310 --> 00:50:37.150
rich, the educated, and those lacking in either.

722
00:50:37.150 --> 00:50:43.160
Why wouldn’t the young, poor, rentboy growing
up on the streets of London be enchanted by

723
00:50:43.160 --> 00:50:48.880
pillow-talk lessons of creatures and heroes
from an era where same-gender attraction was

724
00:50:48.880 --> 00:50:50.260
not so taboo?

725
00:50:50.260 --> 00:50:58.059
In which case, I may be suggesting that our
love of monsters — both academic and fetishistic

726
00:50:58.059 --> 00:51:04.240
— is a matter of carrying on the stories
and traditions from pagan cultures where our

727
00:51:04.240 --> 00:51:10.660
identities and expressions of sexuality did
not hold the same taboo, as it has for the

728
00:51:10.660 --> 00:51:15.340
last fifteen hundred years.

729
00:51:15.340 --> 00:51:22.400
This proves to us that a world can exist where
we can live without homophobic and transphobic

730
00:51:22.400 --> 00:51:23.400
baggage.

731
00:51:23.400 --> 00:51:29.730
Our freedom, our pride, does not need to be
fiction because our ancestors got by just

732
00:51:29.730 --> 00:51:31.870
fine without homophobia.

733
00:51:31.870 --> 00:51:39.660
We see that homophobia is in contradiction
to social cohesion, progress, social institutions,

734
00:51:39.660 --> 00:51:43.990
trade, commerce, or family structures.

735
00:51:43.990 --> 00:51:48.270
Maybe that gives us hope that it could be
different one day, or that we could eek out

736
00:51:48.270 --> 00:51:55.460
our own existence where we can make this once-truth
a present day reality.

737
00:51:55.460 --> 00:52:00.970
The need to build a community has translated
into the trope of found family.

738
00:52:00.970 --> 00:52:06.470
Which itself is a defense mechanism from — to
this day — living in a world where your

739
00:52:06.470 --> 00:52:15.540
family may push you out if you don’t fit
their checklist of acceptable identities.

740
00:52:15.540 --> 00:52:21.050
Found family wasn’t intended to be a fiction
trope about a plucky group of misfits coming

741
00:52:21.050 --> 00:52:24.150
together for a shared purpose.

742
00:52:24.150 --> 00:52:31.271
It was necessary for queer survival — not
for the survival of our community… no, actual

743
00:52:31.271 --> 00:52:33.840
survival of individuals.

744
00:52:33.840 --> 00:52:40.260
The alternative was filling the streets with
disowned and desperate queer youth.

745
00:52:40.260 --> 00:52:46.560
And if there is one area where fiction and
reality overlap, it’s that monsters feed

746
00:52:46.560 --> 00:52:47.830
on desperation.

747
00:52:47.830 --> 00:52:54.610
There are quiet corners of queer history that
we’ve omitted from the discussion at large.

748
00:52:54.610 --> 00:53:00.750
These are specifically rooted in white colonial
circles; and subsequently focused on a dynamic

749
00:53:00.750 --> 00:53:05.100
of privilege, power, and exploitation.

750
00:53:05.100 --> 00:53:10.171
Given that queer identity for a large section
of history was, itself, illegal, there were

751
00:53:10.171 --> 00:53:16.740
almost no legislative protections that queer
people would have been able to seek out.

752
00:53:16.740 --> 00:53:22.700
Doubly true is that law enforcement itself
has had a history of targeting queer individuals

753
00:53:22.700 --> 00:53:24.900
and whole communities alike.

754
00:53:24.900 --> 00:53:31.940
A gay street kid who gets assaulted by an
established, closeted man has no legal recourse.

755
00:53:31.940 --> 00:53:38.860
But even more unsettling are the ways that
we, as disowned and desperate people, tolerated

756
00:53:38.860 --> 00:53:45.570
these abusive partners simply because the
alternative was a never-ending cycle of shelters,

757
00:53:45.570 --> 00:53:48.120
dark allies, and drugs.

758
00:53:48.120 --> 00:53:54.010
As an example, the culture of the ‘houseboy’
had been a staple of the gay community, and

759
00:53:54.010 --> 00:53:58.890
to some, an indication of status and success.

760
00:53:58.890 --> 00:54:03.980
Wealthy gays taking on young gay men, offering
room and board in exchange for eye candy,

761
00:54:03.980 --> 00:54:07.450
performing household chores, and sexual favours.

762
00:54:07.450 --> 00:54:14.010
The latter of which would often be extended
to friends and guests, at the patron’s whim.

763
00:54:14.010 --> 00:54:21.740
The end result was a socially-accepted precedence
for a power dynamic that exploited vulnerability.

764
00:54:21.740 --> 00:54:28.680
That isn’t to say that all those who provided
shelter to younger gay men were predatory.

765
00:54:28.680 --> 00:54:34.740
That also isn’t to say that all of these
arrangements violated consent.

766
00:54:34.740 --> 00:54:39.900
But the fact that it was so accepted as status-quo
is what should be troubling.

767
00:54:39.900 --> 00:54:44.490
But the power dynamic within the culture certainly
made for an enticing opportunity for some

768
00:54:44.490 --> 00:54:52.260
— to match the monstrous elements of themselves
with the perceived success that home-cleaning

769
00:54:52.260 --> 00:54:55.650
concubines indicated to other queers.

770
00:54:55.650 --> 00:55:02.140
We may never know the degree of exploitation
that has occurred within this very community.

771
00:55:02.140 --> 00:55:08.800
Because there are good Samaritans in the world,
who do aim for the comfort of others.

772
00:55:08.800 --> 00:55:14.990
But for each one of these, how many are there
who get drunk off of having a desperate boy

773
00:55:14.990 --> 00:55:16.500
at their mercy?

774
00:55:16.500 --> 00:55:19.970
The monster, after all, does not know it is
a monster.

775
00:55:19.970 --> 00:55:26.810
A monster is as they have always been: they
do what is natural to them.

776
00:55:26.810 --> 00:55:32.520
And it is those outside who place labels on
the monster.

777
00:55:32.520 --> 00:55:39.190
Or, are we so desperate to live out these
monster fables that we seek them out?

778
00:55:39.190 --> 00:55:46.020
We want to be both damsels in need of rescue,
and also chrome-clad knights.

779
00:55:46.020 --> 00:55:52.050
And it may not be the princess or Prince we
want to save from the monster, but the monster

780
00:55:52.050 --> 00:55:53.460
from itself.

781
00:55:53.460 --> 00:55:58.780
Through the process of wanting to redeem the
monster in ourselves, we may seek out other

782
00:55:58.780 --> 00:56:06.420
monsters who neither see the need for their
own redemption nor do they feel that they

783
00:56:06.420 --> 00:56:10.220
do anything requiring redemption.

784
00:56:10.220 --> 00:56:16.230
With them we remain, sinking into habits and
patterns, where their monstrous behaviour

785
00:56:16.230 --> 00:56:20.480
becomes our normal over time.

786
00:56:20.480 --> 00:56:24.180
And those watching us simply cannot understand
why.

787
00:56:24.180 --> 00:56:30.840
This is by no way something only present in
queer circles, but we tend to frame our lives

788
00:56:30.840 --> 00:56:34.200
in ways that mimmic the media we watch.

789
00:56:34.200 --> 00:56:39.750
We see these squabbles, these fights, these
struggles play out over a few seasons of television,

790
00:56:39.750 --> 00:56:42.580
or over the course of a film.

791
00:56:42.580 --> 00:56:49.680
We feel this immense fulfilment over seeing
a satisfying conclusion, over the resolution

792
00:56:49.680 --> 00:56:56.670
of drama, the poetic justice of everyone finally
understanding your side of the story, after

793
00:56:56.670 --> 00:57:01.520
the evil monster is recognized as a sympathetic
man.

794
00:57:01.520 --> 00:57:08.990
And everyone just decides to forgive and forget
the ways they hurt others.

795
00:57:08.990 --> 00:57:11.310
But Real life doesn’t have a plot.

796
00:57:11.310 --> 00:57:16.150
Real life does not have a resolution and nor
will there ever be.

797
00:57:16.150 --> 00:57:19.160
Not as we’d understand it.

798
00:57:19.160 --> 00:57:25.970
So our attempts to find meaning and significance
in what happens is a matter of us superimposing

799
00:57:25.970 --> 00:57:32.340
our own understanding of literary devices
and dramatic licence upon the events that

800
00:57:32.340 --> 00:57:34.790
happen around us in real life.

801
00:57:34.790 --> 00:57:43.390
And always in a way which feed into our own
story, our own character development.

802
00:57:43.390 --> 00:57:50.830
And some of us want our story to be about
turning the beast into a prince.

803
00:57:50.830 --> 00:57:56.990
I can’t think of a single queer person who
has not gone through some kind of abusive

804
00:57:56.990 --> 00:58:02.750
relationship – and that’s even outside
our garden-variety trauma.

805
00:58:02.750 --> 00:58:09.850
We all have that one ex who, if they didn’t
outright abuse us, treated us like they were

806
00:58:09.850 --> 00:58:12.550
the most important thing in our lives.

807
00:58:12.550 --> 00:58:15.820
Like we couldn't exist without them.

808
00:58:15.820 --> 00:58:18.310
Some of us have more than one, of course.

809
00:58:18.310 --> 00:58:23.280
And yet… we all know exactly why we stuck
around for so long.

810
00:58:23.280 --> 00:58:27.100
Why we tolerated the behaviour, the treatment.

811
00:58:27.100 --> 00:58:31.280
Because the alternative was being alone.

812
00:58:31.280 --> 00:58:37.250
The alternative was not being understood.

813
00:58:37.250 --> 00:58:45.380
Even if the alternative was not explicit rejection,
maybe it’s just as bad to earn indifference.

814
00:58:45.380 --> 00:58:46.820
And regardless of the behaviour…

815
00:58:46.820 --> 00:58:48.910
That one person ‘got’ you.

816
00:58:48.910 --> 00:58:50.570
They understood you.

817
00:58:50.570 --> 00:58:55.690
In fact, that kind of emotional proximity
is exactly why they were able to twist you

818
00:58:55.690 --> 00:59:00.420
around the rusty nails they pounded into your
heart.

819
00:59:00.420 --> 00:59:07.820
They knew where your heart was… when nobody
else cared enough to look for it.

820
00:59:07.820 --> 00:59:09.760
And leaving them?

821
00:59:09.760 --> 00:59:14.270
Even if you did find somebody else… would
they ever understand you the way the monster

822
00:59:14.270 --> 00:59:16.800
had?

823
00:59:16.800 --> 00:59:23.160
Human survival has depended on establishing
connections with others.

824
00:59:23.160 --> 00:59:29.740
So how can anyone say that it’s your fault
for craving that connection with a monster

825
00:59:29.740 --> 00:59:38.400
over no connection at all?

826
00:59:38.400 --> 00:59:43.510
So much of queer horror is about the aspects
of our culture that straight people fear,

827
00:59:43.510 --> 00:59:49.120
that straight society fears: women's strength
and independence, men's vulnerability and

828
00:59:49.120 --> 00:59:55.680
intimacy, the upending of gender and family
roles, the rejection of the primacy of reproduction,

829
00:59:55.680 --> 01:00:01.630
the hollowness and bankruptcy of the dominant
social structures, and challenges to the Church's

830
01:00:01.630 --> 01:00:03.200
pronouncements.

831
01:00:03.200 --> 01:00:09.960
And our inherent invisibility, our cunning—that
we might be anyone, anywhere, lurking in plain

832
01:00:09.960 --> 01:00:10.960
sight.

833
01:00:10.960 --> 01:00:16.610
I have to confess, there's something delectable
about the fact that we would cause so much

834
01:00:16.610 --> 01:00:23.200
anxiety, and anguish, and unreasonable, unwarranted
fear simply by existing.

835
01:00:23.200 --> 01:00:26.840
There seems to be great power in that.

836
01:00:26.840 --> 01:00:30.120
Aside from the obvious, what are queer people
terrified of?

837
01:00:30.120 --> 01:00:37.180
Of course, we are scared of death, as well
as violence, torture, sickness, and suffering,

838
01:00:37.180 --> 01:00:41.520
as well as being exposed, humiliated, shunned,
and persecuted.

839
01:00:41.520 --> 01:00:46.590
We are concerned about being erased, unseen,
or forgotten.

840
01:00:46.590 --> 01:00:48.860
We're terrified of being alone.

841
01:00:48.860 --> 01:00:54.270
But being queer is sometimes about all of
those things; they are at the heart of our

842
01:00:54.270 --> 01:00:57.260
history and the source of our oppression.

843
01:00:57.260 --> 01:01:03.230
Being queer sometimes means being cast out;
other times, it means casting ourselves out,

844
01:01:03.230 --> 01:01:09.540
walking or running away from abusive families
and partners while we still can.

845
01:01:09.540 --> 01:01:13.580
Being queer sometimes means being the sympathetic
beast.

846
01:01:13.580 --> 01:01:15.850
Frankenstein’s monster.

847
01:01:15.850 --> 01:01:17.280
Just yearning to be left alone.

848
01:01:17.280 --> 01:01:19.090
To live our lives.

849
01:01:19.090 --> 01:01:24.820
Depending upon where in the world you live
being queer can mean losing your family, your

850
01:01:24.820 --> 01:01:25.900
friends, your religion.

851
01:01:25.900 --> 01:01:31.240
The pillars of society that held you up and
now you’re left alone, forced to fight for

852
01:01:31.240 --> 01:01:35.700
yourself because sometimes no one else is
willing to fight for you.

853
01:01:35.700 --> 01:01:40.190
Like the victim of a slasher movie, you’ve
watched as everything and everyone you held

854
01:01:40.190 --> 01:01:42.770
dear drops around you.

855
01:01:42.770 --> 01:01:44.720
But there’s strength there.

856
01:01:44.720 --> 01:01:53.550
Because sometimes, after everything and everyone
has been stripped from us, sometimes being

857
01:01:53.550 --> 01:01:58.099
queer means being the last one standing.